Luna is an adorable newer female who came from an animal shelter. She’s about 3 years old but still as active as a pup and she’s strong despite her smaller size. We are glad we were able to spay her right away because it turned out she was in the beginning stages of pyometra! It’s a nasty infection of the uterus and we (unknowingly) got to her just in time. Luna still needs to gain a few pounds but she’s doing very well recovering from her surgery. She is dog social and LOVES people but her behavior on leash needs a little help because she just gets so excited and will bark at other dogs. She’s working on it. She also needs secure fence material since she has put a couple holes in a chain link kennel piece to escape. She follows us right back to the kennel so clearly she’s just looking for company but it could be dangerous if she doesn’t have some kind of solid fencing in her new home. Luna will be a devoted, silly and playful companion for someone equally devoted to her.

Meet one of our new additions. This sweet, middle aged angel came to us yesterday from one of the many overcrowded animal shelters. She was found as a stray, clearly bred multiple times, she has paint stuck to her fur and she was beaten up significantly by a shepherd she was found with. This poor girl needed a break. The shelter vet spayed her, stitched up her wounds and removed a growth so we paid a little extra for her rescue. How about we do a little fundraiser and get some help from all of you to find her a new name? Make a suggestion in the comments section below and make a donation to help us out. It can be $1 or $100 and we’re going on the honor system here everyone. Every dollar counts at the rescue and helps us keep this train moving so we appreciate all of your help, big or small. We will choose one of our suggested names tomorrow and get this sweet girl healed so she can find a loving forever home. Note: so far she’s been good around other dogs, cats and she wants to be glued to a person’s side but she’s a little shut down so we will see how she does in the coming days. 💕

New boy Cairo had a big day yesterday. He had his first bath, got his ear cleaned out, ate his bravecto (kills mange mites) and we started him on some heavy duty antibiotics for his upper respiratory infection. He is in good spirits, loves his walks (even though his feet are quite sensitive), and he’s eating like a champ. Get ready for the transformation on this one. We’ve got you buddy. 💕

There are many realities in rescue that we realize aren’t known by the public so we’d like to gently shed some light on a consistent phenomenon we see. We get difficult medical cases and emaciated dogs in all the time but we don’t usually share new dogs until they’re healthy, spayed/neutered and ready for adoption. Some may ask why since most rescues share from the moment a dog comes in. Well, what usually happens is that we get a lot of interest in that one brand new dog (currently Cairo) despite us not really knowing much about them behaviorally or what their health will look like long-term or when they may even be ready for adoption. In the meantime, we have a ton of wonderful dogs who are healthy, ready for adoption and great choices for loving homes. The sad truth is that we can’t continue to rescue more dogs like Cairo unless current dogs get adopted and we then have the space to do so. It’s frustrating to have a dozen people want 1 dog and no one interested in the others. Often times, weeks later when they are healthy and no longer the really sad looking dog, many interest parties then disappear. While we appreciate the outpouring of love and we can certainly use the donations, please don’t let a sad story be the reason you choose a dog. Every dog waiting for a home is worthy of one and we would be happy to help you find the right match for your family when you are ready! You can see our available dogs on our website at www.dobiesandlittlepawsrescue.org and we are adding more this week.

This is certainly not the update we were hoping for. We just received a call from Jagger’s doctor and the news was devastating. The internal medicine team did an ultrasound and found a significant mass in Jagger’s stomach. They also detected some abnormalities in his kidneys. Thr pneumonia was probably secondary to a whole lot of other internal problems we never knew were lurking. The vet suspected lymphoma based on these and other test results but without a biopsy we don’t know for sure which cancer he’s dealing with. An endoscopy would need to be performed and Jagger is not stable enough to go thru that procedure. Even if we could  treat his immediately life threatening symptoms, he would only have months to live and he wouldn’t have quality of life. I put a little something together last night as a tribute and a thank you to all of you. The sadness and frustration of the rescue world lately due to the huge influx of animals in need has been tough. It’s easy to become bitter and so many utter the phrase “I hate people”. The truth is, people are what make rescue possible. People are the volunteers that give up their time to give the dogs some love, people are the ones who donate funds so vet bills and food bills can be paid, people are the ones who take a deserving dog waiting for a second chance and give them a home and a family. Seeing the outpouring of photos and videos yesterday was just incredible. (I’m so sorry to the later messages that came in but I sincerely thank you for sharing!) I couldn’t share all of them that I wanted to because there were so many. Thank you for sharing your memories, your families, and the kind words that many of you included as well. I can speak for the rescue as a whole, we appreciate every one of you and thank you for being a part of Dobies and Little Paws. Let’s spread some love today, some light, and some joy. Thank you.

-Colleen

Meet Miracle! Hang in there because this little lady has quite the sorry. Miracle was in an animal shelter with a badly broken leg. So bad that we full expected she would require an amputation. However, the incredible vets at Abby Vet Hospital in Fresno were able to put her leg back together and she made a full recovery. Amazing! Also, kind of how she got her name. Miracle went in for a routine spay last Friday and all went well during surgery. She had a little bleeding when we went to pick her up (not uncommon) but the vet inspected the incision and it appeared to be a skin bleed (not internal bleeding) which usually resolves itself with a pressure bandage and a clotting supplement (both of which she got). By the time we made it back to the rescue that evening there was blood soaked thru the blanket she was sleeping on. We called all of the emergency vets because she was still actively bleeding but everyone was full or closed. Thankfully, ACCESS Pasadena could see us so after a long day, we made it out there late at night. It was mostly good news. All tests showed that Miracle has no clotting issues and her blood work was good. She went in for surgery that night and the problem was fixed quite easily. She had a couple of blood vessels in the subcutaneous skin later that just wouldn’t stop bleeding so those were cauterized and she was closed back up with no further complications. Before anyone jumps to conclusions, this was no vet error or a mistake but simply one of the many possible complications that can happen because of surgery. Now, miracle needs the hardware taken off of her injured leg because her skin will not stay closed over the metal plate and it’s risking infection. Her leg is healed so she no longer needs it but we have to get her in for another surgery to have it removed. Ok if this means some fundraising is needed! Her detour to the emergency vet totaled $2,700 and we are waiting on word from our vets to get an estimate on her plate removal. If you can spare a few bucks for our sweet girl then we can cover these medical costs and get her back on the road to a new home!

I want to preface Rebel’s story and this post by saying that the comments section will not be a place to argue the ethics or legalities of ear cropping. There are plenty of places on the internet where you can go and argue but our page is not one of them. We want to stay focused on the dogs. Ear cropping by a licensed veterinarian is legal in the U.S. but this story is about animal cruelty, plain and simple.

Rebel is an approximately 5-month-old puppy that was brought into a vet clinic to be euthanized about 6 weeks ago. Why? His ears were infected. Someone held him down and without a vet or anesthesia they cut his ears. Not cropped…cut. It was clear this person had no idea what they were doing and Rebel’s ears were mangled. Thankfully, the vet refused to euthanize a healthy puppy, had him surrendered and they contacted us. It took a few weeks for him to recover from the upper respiratory infection he had and in that time his ears healed. We did have the tip of one of them fixed this week while he was being neutered so it wouldn’t cause long-term issues. The resilience of dogs continues to amaze us because despite what he went thru at the hands of humans, Rebel is the most confident, outgoing, happy puppy you will ever meet. Everyone is his friend and he plays non-stop. He’s ready to find a forever home and we hope he will have nothing but wonderful things in life for him from now on. He is vocal when left alone so he should have another dog (or 2) to play with and an inclusive home where he can burn off his energy.

Some of you may recognize this adorable guy from a post a little while back asking for name suggestions. Well, meet Ren! We have been thru a lot with him and he still has a ways to go before he’s ready for a new home.

Ren landed at a rural animal shelter with a badly hurt back leg. He had chewed thru an old bandage wrapped around his leg and his foot was severely damaged. We picked him up and he has been on heavy antibiotics as well as getting daily bandage wraps ever since. Thankfully, we got the raging infection under control and his wounds started to heal. We had our suspicions as to what happened and X-rays showed we were probably right. He suffered a fracture around the tarsus and we think someone wrapped his leg in a makeshift splint. The bandage was either too tight and/or left on too long causing permanent damage to Ren’s foot. The fracture has healed but the necrotic infection he suffered caused Ren to lose all of his toes. He went to the vet yesterday to have the remaining exposed toe bones removed so his foot could continue healing. We have considered amputation throughout his healing journey since we didn’t know if he would have a functioning leg but we always keep that as a last option since it’s harder for large dogs as they age. His large foot pad remains intact and he is walking on his leg so we are hopeful for Ren’s future with all 4 legs. He will require a boot on that foot for the rest of his life to keep it protected but he should be able to function normally. We are also expecting him to start gaining weight now that his body isn’t in survival mode and he’s not fighting systemic infections. Ren is young and the absolute sweetest dog you’ll ever meet. He wants to snuggle during every bandage change and never complains. He will eventually need a special home that can care for his needs but right now he’s focused on finishing his healing journey. 💕

Ren is only one of our current medical cases at the moment and while we know not everyone is in a position to give, we could really use some help if you’re able. Thank you so much everyone. 💕

Meet Schatzi, a spirited 4-year-old Doberman Pinscher mix who’s got enough energy to light up a room! Schatzi is as fun as her name suggests, and she loves nothing more than a game of fetch or a long walk to expend some of that boundless zest for life. Schatzi is not keen on bicycles, so a home without them would be her haven. She adores raw bones and tennis balls; offer her either, and you'll have a friend for life. She’s also on the lookout for a foodie partner-in-crime. Yes, this girl loves her treats! 

Due to a move, we have to find this sweet and lively girl a new home. What Schatzi needs is someone who can match her boundless energy and offer her a loving, forever home. With a little attention to her quirks, she’s going to make someone an incredibly loyal and joyful companion.
